\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 1.              Salix}                L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By K.H. Rechinger (Ed.1) revised by J.R. Akeroyd (Ed.2)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Buds with 1 outer scale. Leaves variously shaped. Flowers primarily entomophilous, appearing before or after the leaves, each flower with 1 or 2 small nectaries and subtended by an entire bract. Stamens usually 2, 3 or 5. Capsule 2-valved.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Although sections have been described in this genus they will not be indicated in the text, since most of them are represented only by a single species or species-group in Europe (with the exception of Sect.{\i  Capreae}, species {\b 38-41}).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Hybridization plays a very important role in{\i  Salix}. Most hybrids are highly fertile, and in some regions hybrid swarms obscure the limits of the species. Complex hybrids are also known. On the other hand certain taxa of evidently hybrid but uncertain origin are fairly well stabilized. These have not been included in the key but are mentioned after the species to which they show most resemblance. It is not possible to provide a separate key for non-flowering plants as there is too much parallel variation in most species in indumentum, leaf-shape, leaf-margin, etc.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The key is therefore based on the rather unrealistic assumption that the plant to be named is represented by branches bearing male catkins, female catkins, and leaves, and that data on its habit and habitat are also available.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Leaf-characters refer to{\i  adult} leaves unless otherwise stated. Catkin-characters refer to the {\i female} catkins unless otherwise stated.
\par

